ss-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in California|California]]\n|open but limited capacity<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrn.com/operations/governors-new-york-illinois-california-and-ohio-call-shut-down-restaurants-and-bars|title=Governors of New York, Illinois, California and Ohio call for shut down of restaurants and bars to prevent spread of coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|website=Nation's Restaurant News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]<ref name=\":41\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hawaii|Hawaii]]<ref name=\":41\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Idaho|Idaho]]\n|March 21<ref name=\":41\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Missouri|Missouri]]<ref name=\":42\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mississippi|Mississippi]]\n|open<ref name=\":42\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oklahoma|Oklahoma]]\n|open<ref name=\":42\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nevada|Nevada]]\n|March 18<ref name=\":42\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Dakota|North Dakota]]<ref name=\":42\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Dakota|South Dakota]]\n|open<ref name=\":42\" />\n|1878<ref name=\":45\">{{Cite web|url=https://restaurant.org/Downloads/PDFs/State-Statistics/southdakota.pdf|title=South Dakota restaurant industry at a glance|last=|first=|date=2019|website=restaurant.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n|48,200<ref name=\":45\" />\n|$1.5 billion<ref name=\":45\" />\n|\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nebraska|Nebraska]]<ref name=\":42\" />\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n=== Federal response ===\nUS President Trump met via phone on March 19 with leaders of chain restaurant companies, but no independent restaurateurs were included.<ref name=\":7\" /> Participants included [[Domino's Pizza]], [[McDonald's]], [[Wendy's]], [[Yum! Brands]] and [[Darden Restaurants]] and representatives from the [[International Franchise Association]] and the [[National Retail Federation]].<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nOn March 25 the White House and Senate leadership came to an agreement on a $2 trillion stimulus package.<ref name=\":43\" /> The bill was reported to include $250 billion in direct payments to individuals, $350 billion for small business loans, $250 billion for unemployment benefits, and $500 billion for loans to troubled companies.<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/stimulus-senate-action-coronavirus/index.html|title=White House, Senate reach historic $2 trillion stimulus deal amid growing coronavirus fears|last=Raju|first=Manu|last2=Barrett|first2=Ted|date=25 March 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25|last3=Foran|first3=Clare|last4=Wilson|first4=Kristin}}</ref> It contains a provision preventing Trump, his family, other top government officials and members of Congress from benefiting from programs and creates an oversight board and inspector general position.<ref name=\":43\" /> Restaurateur and chef Tom Colicchio, who had been active in asking for a government rescue of the industry, later that day said he was feeling \"optimistic\" about the package.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/top-chef-star-tom-colicchio-restaurants-coronavirus-outbreak|title='Top Chef' star Tom Colicchio on crisis facing restaurant industry: 'Our workers are really hurting'|last=Kaplan|first=Talia|date=2020-03-25|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Economy of the United States]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in the United States]]\n[[Category:Consequences of events]]\n[[Category:Aftermath of events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Impact of COVID-19}}\n[[File:Graeter&#039;s coronavirus sign 24 March 2020.jpg|thumb|Signs on door of a [[Graeter's]] ice cream parlor during government-mandated closings|alt=Signs read \"We're open, carryout & order pickup only at this time. Get it delivered.\" and \"Please keep social distancing in mind. Keep 6 feet apart from one another. Please take  your order to go once received. Thank you for helping us comply with govermental health recommedations.\"]]\nThe 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic impacted the [[US restaurant industry]] via government closures, resulting in layoffs of workers and loss of income for restaurants and owners and threatening the survival of independent restaurants as a category. Within a week after the first closures, industry groups representing independent restaurateurs were asking for immediate relief measures from local, state, and federal governments, saying that as many as 75% of independent restaurants could not survive closures of more than a few weeks.\n\nRestaurant closures started March 15 when Ohio Governor Mike DeWine ordered all bars and restaurants in the state to close their dining rooms and bars; within a week most other states followed suit. By March 23 industry experts were estimating nearly half of the industry's 15 million workers had been laid off. Insurers refused to cover the restaurants' financial losses via business interruption policies.\n\nAcross the world, restaurants' daily traffic dropped precipitously as compared to the same period in 2019 as the [[Impact of the coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry|coronavirus impacted the overall industry]]. Closures of restaurants caused a ripple effect among dependent industries such as food production, liquor, wine, and beer production, shipping, linen suppliers, fishing and farming and among musicians, florists, and delivery services.\n\n==Industry background==\nThe US restaurant industry was projected at $899 billion in sales for 2020 by the [[National Restaurant Association]], the main trade association for the industry in the United States.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2020/03/20/cincinnati-restaurants-ask-feds-for-coronavirus.html|title=Cincinnati restaurants ask feds for coronavirus bailout|last=Brownfield|first=Andy|date=20 March 2020|website=login.research.cincinnatilibrary.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":17\" /> An estimated 99% of companies in the industry are family-owned small businesses with fewer than 50 employees.<ref name=\":14\" /> The industry as a whole as of February 2020 employed more than 15 million people, representing 10% of the workforce directly.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is the nation's second largest private employer and the third largest employer overall.<ref name=\":102\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/22/819189939/closed-all-at-once-restaurant-industry-faces-collapse|title=Closed All At Once: Restaurant Industry Faces Collapse|last=Noguchi|first=Yuki|date=22 March 2020|website=NPR.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/stephanie-ruhle/watch/restaurant-industry-reeling-from-coronavirus-80967237571|title=Restaurant industry reeling from coronavirus|website=MSNBC.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> It indirectly employed close to another 10% when dependent businesses such as food producers, trucking, and delivery services were factored in, according to Ohio restaurateur Britney Ruby Miller.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ancillary industries such as food purveyors, linen suppliers, florists, farming, fishing, trucking, beverages depend on the restaurant industry for their own financial health.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":14\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/coronavirus/2020/03/23/nj-coronavirus-covid-19-pandemic-devastates-restaurants/2868629001/|title='We are in survival mode': Coronavirus devastates New Jersey restaurants|last=Davidowitz|first=Esther|website=North Jersey|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/artsandlife/article/coronavirus-food-industry-portland-oregon-impacts-four-top/|title='The Four Top': Coronavirus Hits The Food Industry|last=Cole|first=Katherine|website=opb.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nIn Delaware and Massachusetts, one in ten workers is employed in the restaurant industry.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> In North Carolina, 11% of workers are employed by the industry.<ref name=\":26\" /> In Texas, 12% of workers were employed by the industry as of 2016.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.txresto.com/newsblog/85-restaurant-industry-in-texas|title=Restaurant Industry In Texas|website=txresto.com|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\nAcross the world, restaurants' daily traffic dropped precipitously as compared to the same period in 2019 as the virus spread.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-restaurant-business-decline-cities/|title=See how much business U.S. restaurants are losing because of the coronavirus|website=cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 28 story about how restaurants could prepare for the possibility of a pandemic, ''[[Restaurant Business]]'' quoted Roslyn Stone, COO of a firm that provides crisis response for restaurants, who said \"The prospect of a global pandemic has already put a spotlight on restaurants and the tendency for employees to come in sick. Though more chains have started giving employees sick time as the supply of labor has tightened, it\u2019s increasingly important for companies to change their culture to ensure employees aren't working while sick.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.restaurantbusinessonline.com/operations/how-restaurants-can-prepare-coronavirus-pandemic|title=How restaurants can prepare for a coronavirus pandemic|last=Maze|first=Jonathan|last2=Feb. 28|first2=Heather Lalley on|website=Restaurant Business|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|last3=2020}}</ref>\n\nA March 3 story in Nation's Restaurant News characterized the industry as being braced for impact from the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrn.com/news/restaurant-industry-braces-coronavirus-impact|title=Restaurant industry braces for coronavirus impact|date=2020-03-03|website=Nation's Restaurant News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nOn Sunday, March 15, Ohio Governor [[Mike DeWine]] and Ohio Health Department director [[Amy Acton]] ordered the closure of all bars and restaurants to help slow the spread of the virus, saying the government \"encouraged restaurants to offer carryout or delivery service, but they would not be allowed to have people congregating in the businesses.\"<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487684-ohio-closing-all-bars-restaurants-in-response-to-coronavirus|title=Illinois, Ohio closing all bars, restaurants in response to coronavirus|last=Conradis|first=Brandon|date=March 15, 2020|website=thehill.com}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/ohio-confirms-first-coronavirus-cases-continues-testing-2020-mar|title=37 confirmed cases of coronavirus in Ohio; 361 under investigation|date=15 March 2020|website=WBNS-10TV Columbus, Ohio {{!}} Columbus News, Weather & Sports|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318055740/https://www.10tv.com/article/ohio-confirms-first-coronavirus-cases-continues-testing-2020-mar|archive-date=18 March 2020|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200315/coronavirus-governor-orders-ohio-bars-restaurants-to-shut-down|title=Coronavirus: Governor orders Ohio bars, restaurants to shut down|date=15 March 2020|publisher=The Columbus Dispatch|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316153943/https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200315/coronavirus-governor-orders-ohio-bars-restaurants-to-shut-down|archive-date=16 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> DeWine said he'd made the decision \"after being contacted by citizens around the state sharing photos and stories of crowded bars Saturday night, despite warnings of social distancing and the governor\u2019s edict limiting crowds to no larger than 100 people.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> The city of Los Angeles closed all restaurants and bars later that evening and New York City announced all restaurants and bars would close by the following Tuesday, both cities also allowing exceptions for takeout and delivery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://la.eater.com/2020/3/15/21180760/los-angeles-bar-restaurant-shutdown-order|title=LA Mayor Eric Garcetti orders closure of restaurants and bars, allowing only takeout and delivery|last=Kang|first=Matthew|date=2020-03-15|website=Eater LA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nThe next day, Illinois, New Jersey, New York state, Connecticut, Kentucky, Pennsylvania, Maryland and Washington, D.C. followed suit.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Witte|first=Griff|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-ohio-dewine-outbreak/2020/03/16/9bde6b1e-67b2-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html|title=Ohio Gov. Mike DeWine's coronavirus response has become a national guide to the crisis|date=16 March 2020|work=Washington Post|access-date=22 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Zezima|first2=Katie}}</ref> By March 21, at least 25 states had closed restaurants and bars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/21/21188210/coronavirus-restaurant-bar-workers-economy-service-industry|title=When coronavirus is behind us, will you still think of restaurant and bar workers?|last=Taylor|first=Luke|date=2020-03-21|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> By March 22 the number had risen to 38.<ref name=\":15\" /> In other states, major cities had closed bars and restaurants to sit-down diners and limited to takeout orders and delivery.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local|title=Chart: How coronavirus is devastating the restaurant business|date=16 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319091659/https://www.vox.com/recode/2020/3/16/21181556/coronavirus-chart-restaurant-business-local|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact of closures==\n[[File:To-go only restaurant.jpg|thumb|A restaurant that is to-go only due to laws created to stop the spread of the coronavirus]]\nAccording to [[NPR]]'s [[Yuki Noguchi]], \"Just about every restaurant nationwide has been hit hard at once, making this disaster unique.\"<ref name=\":102\"/> Industry experts warned that many small businesses would not be able to recover from closures without help from the government.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/business-a-lobbying/488110-restaurant-industry-reeling-under-coronavirus|title=Restaurant industry reeling under coronavirus|last=Mali|first=Meghashyam|date=2020-03-17|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Impact on the greater economy was as of March 17 expected to be large as Americans have in recent years spent more at restaurants than at grocery stores.<ref name=\":14\" /> Lester Jones, chief economist of the [[National Beer Wholesalers Association]], said \u201cThis is a very significant and traumatic event for the restaurants, bars, taverns and the industry in general.\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Chris Swonger, CED of the Distilled Spirits Council of the United States, said \"The impact on our industry is going to be really, really difficult. It's going to be a real challenge economically for not only the distillers of the United States, but certainly small businesses, restaurants, and bars.\"<ref name=\":14\" /> Sean Kennedy of the National Restaurant Association on March 19 called the closures a \"perfect storm\" for the industry, saying the three primary challenges for restaurateurs are short-term access to cash, medium and long-term access to credit, and tax relief when the closures are ended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818192556/food-and-beverage-industry-hit-hard-by-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Food And Beverage Industry Hit Hard By Coronavirus Outbreak|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> An investor in two New York City restaurants told the New York Post:<ref name=\":37\" />\n\n{{Quote|text=This situation is apocalyptic for the restaurant business. How sad would the city be if the only places that survived were chains? It makes me depressed to even think about it.\u201d|author=Mark Amadei|title=|source=}}\n\nThe ''New York Times'' on March 20 reported that industry analysts were predicting that two-thirds of restaurants would not survive, and as many as 75% of independents.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Severson|first=Kim|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/dining/local-restaurants-coronavirus.html|title=Independent Restaurants Brace for the Unknown|date=2020-03-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-23|last2=Yaffe-Bellany|first2=David|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n''[[Forbes]]'' on March 19 estimated the job losses in the restaurant industry to be in the millions.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/elvaramirez/2020/03/19/the-restaurant-industry-needs-a-coronavirus-bailout-will-they-get-it/|title=The Restaurant Industry Needs A Coronavirus Bailout. Will They Get It?|last=Ramirez|first=Elva|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> The National Restaurant Association estimated probable job losses to be five to seven million.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nIndustry experts on March 18 forecasted $225 billion in direct losses and a full economic impact of $675 billion because of additional revenues generated elsewhere in the economy when customers patronize restaurants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/business-a-lobbying/488223-restaurant-industry-estimates-225b-in-losses-from|title=Restaurant industry estimates $225B in losses from coronavirus|last=Gangitano|first=Alex|date=2020-03-18|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>[[Tom Colicchio]], speaking with [[Yahoo! Finance|Yahoo Finance]] on March 23, and other industry experts said the [[United States restaurant industry|US restaurant industry]] had seen as many 7 million layoffs.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/video/restaurateur-chef-tom-colicchio-effects-212303914.html|title=Restaurateur and Chef Tom Colicchio on how coronavirus is impacting the restaurant industry|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=\":30\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/food-drink/seattles-best-restaurants-asking-for-help-from-congress-and-from-you/|title=Seattle's best restaurants asking for help from Congress \u2014 and from you|date=2020-03-23|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable closings ===\n[[File:Starbucks closure.jpg|thumb|A Starbucks closed due to coronavirus laws in North Carolina]]\nOn March 20, McDonald's closed 50 restaurants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrn.com/quick-service/coronavirus-pandemic-prompts-mcdonalds-temporarily-close-50-restaurants|title=Coronavirus pandemic prompts McDonald's to temporarily close 50 restaurants|date=2020-03-20|website=Nation's Restaurant News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On March 21, Starbucks announced company-operated stores in the US and Canada would be limited to drive-thru and delivery orders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrn.com/quick-service/starbucks-closes-cafes-limits-orders-delivery-and-drive-thru|title=Starbucks closes cafes, limits orders to delivery and drive-thru|date=2020-03-21|website=Nation's Restaurant News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>[[Union Square Hospitality Group]], which the ''New York Post'' described as \"largely seen as the gold standard for employment practices in the industry,\" laid off 2000 employees March 13.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/22/laid-off-eatery-workers-face-health-insurance-crisis-amid-coronavirus/|title=Laid-off eatery workers face health-insurance crisis amid coronavirus|last=Fickenscher|first=Lisa|last2=Keil|first2=Jennifer Gould|date=2020-03-23|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Industry fallout and reactions ===\nThe partial rather than full closings of restaurants meant that the closings failed to trigger business interruption insurance for many restaurants;<ref name=\":102\"/> other policies had clauses excluding coverage in the case of epidemics, action by civil authority, or requiring restaurants to have physical damage to property.<ref name=\":39\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2020/3/20/21188798/restaurant-insurance-coronavirus-covid-19-claims-denied|title=Why Are Insurance Companies Denying Restaurant Claims in Wake of Pandemic?|last=Sedacca|first=Matthew|date=2020-03-20|website=Eater|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=\":40\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fosters.com/news/20200323/denied-restaurant-owners-find-insurance-wonrsquot-cover-coronavirus-losses|title=Denied: Restaurant owners find insurance won't cover coronavirus losses|last=Sullivan|first=Max|date=23 March 2020|website=fosters.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> One industry representative said forcing insurers to cover business interruption claims would bankrupt the insurance industry.<ref name=\":40\" />\n\nAs many as 7 million workers were estimated to have been laid off by March 23,<ref name=\":18\" /><ref name=\":30\" /> and more employees lacked [[sick leave]] in the sector compared to similar sectors.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/|title=Coronavirus exposes sick leave gap for retail, restaurant workers|date=17 March 2020|website=Press Enterprise|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318153437/https://www.pe.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-exposes-sick-leave-gap-for-retail-restaurant-workers/|archive-date=18 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">[http://www.nber.org/papers/w26832.pdf Sick leave] ''[[National Bureau of Economic Research]]''</ref> The ''New York Times'' characterized the closures as affecting \"all strata of the industry, from the owners and their celebrity chefs to the waiters and waitresses, bar-backs and busboys, who effectively are facing layoffs and may be unable to pay their rent.\"<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|last=Wilson|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/nyregion/nyc-closing-bars-restaurants-coronavirus.html|title='We're Completely Lost': Coronavirus Hits N.Y. Restaurants|date=2020-03-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-22|last2=Nierenberg|first2=Amelia|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nSome restaurants whose business already relied heavily on takeout, such as pizza parlors, saw their takeout business decrease due to the cancellation of all sporting events, which \"drive pizza sales\" according to one Ohio pizza shop owner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/16/816658217/ohio-restaurant-owner-reacts-to-closing-due-to-coronavirus|title=Ohio Restaurant Owner Reacts To Closing Due To Coronavirus|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Industry experts have said that takeout and delivery service will also see reduced demand and won't be able to make up the shortfall for restaurants.<ref name=\":14\" /> Some restaurants closed down, some turned to pickup and delivery, and some began doing grocery delivery or meal kit services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrn.com/operations/restaurants-pivot-groceries-and-meal-kits-save-business-during-covid-19-pandemic|title=Restaurants pivot to groceries and meal kits to save business during the COVID-19 pandemic|date=2020-03-20|website=Restaurant Hospitality|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On March 23 the New York Post reported that many New York City restaurants were closing down takeout and delivery due to health concerns for employees and because those businesses weren't bringing in enough money.<ref name=\":37\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/23/nyc-restaurants-stop-offering-takeout-due-to-coronavirus-crisis/|title=NYC restaurants stop offering takeout due to coronavirus crisis|last=Keil|first=Jennifer Gould|date=2020-03-23|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18 the National Restaurant Association asked the federal government for at least $145 billion to provide relief to restaurants and restaurant workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://restaurant.org/Downloads/PDFs/business/Natl-Rest-Association-COVID-Letter|title=Natl Rest. Association COVID Response Ltr|last=|first=|date=18 March 2020|website=National Restaurant Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/coronavirus-stimulus-package-lobbyists-have-asked-us-government-for-more-than-23-trillion-in-aid-2020-03-24|title=Here's everything lobbyists wanted in the coronavirus stimulus package|last=Reklaitis|first=Victor|website=MarketWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nGroups of restaurateurs in New York City, Cincinnati, Philadelphia and Seattle called on governments to provide help to the nation's small and independent restaurants.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> On March 19 the New York group called for state governments to issue orders for rent abatements, suspension of sales and payroll taxes, and a full shutdown so that business interruption insurance coverage would be triggered.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://ny.eater.com/2020/3/19/21187117/momofuku-major-food-group-starr-restaurants-relief-coronavirus-nyc|title=NYC's Top Restaurant Groups Band Together to Petition for Government Relief|last=Adams|first=Erika|date=2020-03-19|website=Eater NY|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On March 20, the Cincinnati group called on the federal government to provide a $225 bailout to the restaurant industry.<ref name=\":0\" /> On March 23 the Philadelphia group asked Pennsylvania<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phillymag.com/foobooz/2020/03/23/coronavirus-petition-restaurants-nicole-marquis/|title=Philly's Biggest Chefs and Restaurateurs Demand Immediate Relief From Government|date=2020-03-23|website=Philadelphia Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> and the Seattle group asked local, state and federal governments to provide relief for laid off workers and closed restaurant businesses.<ref name=\":30\" />\n\n[[Jos\u00e9 Andr\u00e9s|Jose Andres]], writing in the ''New York Times'' on March 22, called on the federal government to fund a food distribution effort that could both feed vulnerable citizens and offer some relief to laid off restaurant workers by employing them to prepare and distribute food where needed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Andr\u00e9s|first=Jos\u00e9|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/22/opinion/restaurants-coronavirus-food-aid.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Jos\u00e9 Andr\u00e9s: We Have a Food Crisis Unfolding Out of Sight|date=2020-03-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n[[Marcus Samuelsson]], writing for CNN.com on March 24, noted as an owner of businesses in eight countries, he has a unique perspective on how the unemployment insurance program in the US compares to programs in other affected countries.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/opinions/coronavirus-restaurant-industry-food-security-samuelsson/index.html|title=Chef: We need seismic change, right now|last=Samuelsson|first=Opinion by Marcus|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The US system, he said, was designed to \"'tide you over' while you quickly find another job\", which is not possible during widespread closures.<ref name=\":8\" /> He called on governments to double the benefits, extend them to 200 or more days, and expand them to include health coverage.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nWith only carry-out and delivery services operating in many states, laid-off servers and bartenders were prompted to create \"virtual tip jars\" across 23 U.S. cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://local12.com/news/local/virtual-tip-jar-website-creates-way-to-help-bartenders-servers-cincinnati|title=Virtual Tip Jar: Website creates way to help bartenders, servers|first=Brad Underwood|last=WKRC|date=23 March 2020|website=WKRC}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\n\n=== State and local government responses ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n|+\nRestaurant closings\n!State or city\n!Date\n!Restaurants\naffected<ref name=\":55\">{{Cite web|url=https://restaurant.org/research/state|title=State Statistics|last=|first=|date=2019|website=National Restaurant Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n!Workers\naffected<ref name=\":55\" />\n!Annual revenue<ref name=\":55\" />\n!Governmental response\n|-\n|[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ohio|Ohio]]\n|March 15\n|22,000<ref name=\":4\">{{cite news|last1=Knall|first1=Amy|url=https://www.cantonrep.com/news/20200316/coronavirus-in-ohio--local-restaurants-react-to-state-ban|title=Local restaurants react to state ban|date=16 March 2020|work=Canton Repository|access-date=16 March 2020|url-st