:7\" /> Participants included [[Domino's Pizza]], [[McDonald's]], [[Wendy's]], [[Yum! Brands]] and [[Darden Restaurants]] and representatives from the [[International Franchise Association]] and the [[National Retail Federation]].<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nOn March 25 the White House and Senate leadership came to an agreement on a $2 trillion stimulus package.<ref name=\":43\" /> The bill was reported to include $250 billion in direct payments to individuals, $350 billion for small business loans, $250 billion for unemployment benefits, and $500 billion for loans to troubled companies.<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/stimulus-senate-action-coronavirus/index.html|title=White House, Senate reach historic $2 trillion stimulus deal amid growing coronavirus fears|last=Raju|first=Manu|last2=Barrett|first2=Ted|date=25 March 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25|last3=Foran|first3=Clare|last4=Wilson|first4=Kristin}}</ref> It contains a provision preventing Trump, his family, other top government officials and members of Congress from benefiting from programs and creates an oversight board and inspector general position.<ref name=\":43\" /> Restaurateur and chef Tom Colicchio, who had been active in asking for a government rescue of the industry, later that day said he was feeling \"optimistic\" about the package.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/top-chef-star-tom-colicchio-restaurants-coronavirus-outbreak|title='Top Chef' star Tom Colicchio on crisis facing restaurant industry: 'Our workers are really hurting'|last=Kaplan|first=Talia|date=2020-03-25|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Economy of the United States]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in the United States]]\n[[Category:Consequences of events]]\n[[Category:Aftermath of events]]\n", "name_user": "Buidhe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_the_restaurant_industry_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Grim's Dyke", "text_new": "{{about||the prehistoric earthworks in southern England|Grim's Ditch|the Roman fortifications in central Scotland|Antonine Wall}}\n[[File:grims-dyke-main.jpg|thumb|300px|The main entrance|alt=]]\n'''Grim's Dyke''' (sometimes called '''Graeme's Dyke''' until late 1891)<ref name=How>How, Harry. [https://www.gsarchive.net/gilbert/interviews/strand_article.html Illustrated Interviews: No. IV \u2013 Mr. W. S. Gilbert\"], ''[[The Strand Magazine]]'', Vol. 2, October 1891, pp. 330\u201341, reprinted at ''The Gilbert and Sullivan Archive'', 20 November 2011</ref> is the name of a house and estate in [[Harrow Weald]], in northwest London, England. The house was built from 1870 to 1872 by [[Richard Norman Shaw]] for painter [[Frederick Goodall]] and named after the nearby prehistoric earthwork known as [[Grim's Ditch (Harrow)|Grim's Ditch]].\n\nThe house is best known as the home of the dramatist [[W. S. Gilbert]], of the opera partnership [[Gilbert and Sullivan]], who lived and farmed there for the last two decades of his life.  He died while attempting to save a girl from drowning in his lake. Lady Gilbert and the Gilberts' ward, [[Nancy McIntosh]], lived there until her death in 1936. The statue of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] now found in [[Soho Square]] stood on the property from about 1880 to 1938. The house was then used as a rehabilitation centre until 1963.\n\nFrom 1963, the house was used mainly as a location for films and television, including ''[[Futtocks End]]'' and ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]''. It was converted into Grim's Dyke Hotel in 1970 but continues to be used as a film location. The hotel retains 30 of the original 110 acres of land that Gilbert purchased with the house.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Grims-Dyke-The-Art-Journal-1881.jpg|thumb|left|Grim's Dyke from the dyke in 1881]]\nThe house was designed in 1870 by [[Richard Norman Shaw]] for the [[Victorian era]] painter [[Frederick Goodall]], who had purchased {{convert|110|acre|km2}} of land<ref>Ainger, p. 320</ref> at [[Harrow Weald]] in 1856, but he did not begin to build until a lease on the property expired.  Shaw's design for the house included aspects of [[Gothic revival]]ism, added to a late-Elizabethan style, which included high red-tiled gables, tall clustered chimneys and leaded lights. To the north of the house, Shaw built a small lodge, a walled garden and various outhouses and a stable block, later converted into garages by [[W. S. Gilbert]] for his collection of motorcars.<ref>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 6</ref> Over the dyke (now a duck pond) Shaw built two stone bridges, which incorporated [[flint]] from the ruined church at [[Stanmore]].<ref>Coincidentally, Gilbert's ashes were buried in the churchyard of this church after his death in 1911.</ref>  Construction on the house was completed in 1872.  Goodall's ground-floor studio was built on a north-south axis in order to catch the light. Goodall sold the property in 1880 to Robert Herriot of [[Hambros Bank]], who added a billiard room in 1883.<ref name=Goodman7>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 7</ref>  [[Windsor Castle]] is visible from the house.<ref name=How/>\n\n[[File:gilbert-library-1891.jpg|thumb|right|[[W.S. Gilbert|Gilbert]] in his library in 1891]]\nW. S. Gilbert purchased the property in August 1890 for \u00a34,000.<ref>Stedman, p. 278.</ref>  He made various additions and alterations to the property, including an elaborate fireplace of Cornish [[alabaster]] in Goodall's studio, which became Gilbert's drawing/music room.  At the house, Gilbert wrote his last ten works from an armchair in his library overlooking the croquet lawn.<ref>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 12</ref>  Gilbert also had an observatory for stargazing.<ref name=How/>\n\n[[Arthur Sullivan]] visited Grim's Dyke with his nephew, [[Herbert Sullivan|Herbert]], on 27 May 1893.<ref>Wolfson, John. ''Final Curtain: The Last Gilbert and Sullivan Operas'', Chappell in association with A. Deutsch, London (1976) p. 28 {{ISBN|0-903443-12-0}}</ref> They stayed at the house for three days while Sullivan worked with Gilbert to finalise ''[[Utopia, Limited]]''.<ref name=\"Goodman Grim's Dyke, p. 17\">Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 17</ref>  At the house, Gilbert had a vinery, [[apiary]], orchards and a farm, with [[Jersey cattle]], horses, pigs and fowl.<ref name=How/>  He also kept a variety of exotic animals including monkeys, lemurs, a lynx and many others.<ref name=Nancy>McIntosh, Nancy.  \"The Late Sir W. S. Gilbert's Pets\", ''Country Life'', 3 June 1911, reprinted in ''W. S. Gilbert Society Journal'', Brian Jones (ed.), Vol. 2, No. 18: Winter 2005, pp. 548\u201356; and McIntosh, Nancy.  \"Sir William Gilbert's Lemurs\", ''The Strand Magazine'', November 1909, vol. 38, pp. 604-09</ref>  Lady Gilbert designed the 30 acres of ornamental gardens at the house, which remain as the hotel grounds.<ref name=Gardens>Glenn, Jill. [http://www.optimamagazine.co.uk/read/leisure/places-to-go/596-lady-gilberts-gardens \"Lady Gilbert's Gardens\"], ''Optima Magazine'', 10 June 2011, accessed January 25, 2012</ref>  After Gilbert's death in 1911, Lady Gilbert and the Gilberts' companion, [[Nancy McIntosh]], continued to live there until Lady Gilbert's own death in 1936.<ref name=Nancy/><ref>Stone, David. [https://www.gsarchive.net/whowaswho/M/McIntoshNancy.htm Nancy McIntosh] at ''Who Was Who in the D'Oyly Carte Opera Company'', 17 August 2005, accessed 3 June 2011</ref>\n\n[[File:Gilbert-library.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Gilbert in the library in later years]]\nAfter Lady Gilbert's death, the contents of the house, apart from a few items kept by Nancy McIntosh, were sold at public auction on 17 and 18 March 1937, realising \u00a34,600. The house was acquired jointly by the [[Middlesex County Council]] and the [[London County Council]], who leased it to the North West Regional Hospital Board from 1937 to 1962, at first as a rehabilitation centre for women suffering from tuberculosis (the house was used by the services during the World War II).<ref name=HistoryPHP>Goodman, Andrew. [http://www.grimsdyke.com/about-us/history/ History], Grimsdyke.com, accessed 26 March 2014</ref>  Following the war, both sexes were admitted,<ref>Goodman, Andrew. ''Gilbert and Sullivan's London'', Hippocrene Books (1988) {{ISBN|0-87052-441-0}}</ref> and from 1948 only male patients were admitted. From 1963, the house was used primarily as a location for films and television, including ''[[Futtock's End]]'' with [[Ronnie Barker]].  It was converted into a hotel in 1970.<ref name=HistoryPHP/> It was featured in John Betjeman's acclaimed television documentary ''[[Metro-Land (1973 film)|Metro-Land]]'' (1973).  The hotel was seen in an [[EastEnders off set episodes#2003|off set episode of ''EastEnders'']] in 2003.\n\nThe house and its gatehouse are both [[listed building]]s.  [[Harrow Council]] owns the building and the remaining 30 acres of the estate and has leased them to the hotel since 1970.<ref name=Gardens/>  The hotel and estate were refurbished in 1996 at a cost of \u00a33 million.<ref name=HistoryPHP/> Presentations of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] operas and other entertainments are regularly held.  The remainder of the lands have been separated from the hotel and are being sold by Harrow Council as \"Grimsdyke Farm\".<ref>[http://www.fwi.co.uk/Articles/2010/01/20/119602/Gilbert-and-Sullivan-estate-up-for-grabs.htm \"Gilbert and Sullivan estate up for grabs\"], Reed Business Information Ltd, 20 January 2010</ref>\n\nThe name Grim's Dyke is sometimes used to refer to a nearby earthwork known as [[Grim's Ditch (Harrow)|Grim's Ditch]] which runs from Pinner Hill to [[RAF Bentley Priory|Bentley Priory]].\n\n==Statue of Charles II==\n[[File:grims-dyke-lake.jpg|thumb|right|260px|The statue of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] in the lake in 1891]]\nA statue of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] was carved by Danish sculptor [[Caius Gabriel Cibber]] in 1681 and placed at the centre of [[Soho Square]] in London.  By the early 19th century, the statue was described as being 'in a most wretched mutilated state; and the inscriptions on the base of the pedestal quite illegible'.<ref name=Cibber>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=41027&strquery=Cibber \"Soho Square Area: Portland Estate: Soho Square Garden\"] in ''Survey of London'' volumes 33 and 34 (1966) St Anne Soho, pp. 51-53. Date accessed: 12 January 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 1875, the statue was removed during alterations in the square by T. Blackwell, of [[Crosse and Blackwell]], the venerable canned and bottled foodstuffs firm, who gave it for safekeeping to his friend, Goodall, with the intention that it might be restored.<ref name=Cibber/>  Goodall placed the statue on an island in his lake at Grim's Dyke, where it remained while Gilbert owned the property.  In her will, Lady Gilbert directed that the statue be returned, and it was restored to Soho Square in 1938.<ref>Minogue, Tim. [http://www.spab.org.uk/cornerstone-magazine/articles-from-cornerstone/soho-farewell-then-/ Soho farewell then\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927120947/http://www.spab.org.uk/cornerstone-magazine/articles-from-cornerstone/soho-farewell-then-/ |date=2011-09-27 }}. SBAP.org, 2009, accessed 2 June 2011</ref>\n\n==Gilbert's lake and death==\nThe lake, which is some way from the house, beyond the ornamental gardens, was considerably extended by Gilbert during his time at Grim's Dyke. Work on digging out the lake began in 1899, with Gilbert himself assisting in the task. Eventually it covered about one and a half [[acre]]s, with an island in the middle, a [[Punt (boat)|punt]] house and changing hut, and an artificial waterfall that was ceremonially turned on in December 1899. The lake was drained and refilled each year, to keep the water clear, and was stocked with [[trout]].<ref>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 14</ref>  In 1905 the lake was extended again to a roughly rectangular shape, measuring 170 [[yard]]s by 50 yards. When Gilbert lived at Grim's Dyke he swam in the lake every day from March to September.<ref name=\"Goodman Grim's Dyke, p. 17\"/>\n[[File:gilberts-lake-1899.jpg|thumb|right|Gilbert's Lake in 1899]]\nOn 29 May 1911 Gilbert had arranged to give a swimming lesson in the lake to two local girls,<ref>Crowther, Andrew. [http://diamond.boisestate.edu/gas/html/gilbert_l.html ''The Life of W. S. Gilbert''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513163810/http://diamond.boisestate.edu/gas/html/gilbert_l.html |date=2008-05-13 }}, The Gilbert and Sullivan Archive, accessed 1 June 2011</ref> Winifred Isabel Emery (1890\u20131972), a teacher<ref>[http://www.1911census.co.uk/search/results5.aspx?x=2080537253 \"76 Weldon Crescent, Harrow County\"]. UK 1911 Census, accessed 6 June 2011 {{subscription}}</ref> and niece of the actors [[Cyril Maude]] and [[Winifred Emery]],<ref>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/76473?docPos=1 Biography] of [[David Gascoyne]], ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', accessed 2 June 2011</ref><ref name=Dark>Dark and Grey, pp. 222\u2013223</ref> and her 17-year-old pupil [[Ruby Vivian Preece]].<ref name=\"Goodman Grim's Dyke, p. 17\"/><ref>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36211?docPos=3 Biography] of [[Stanley Spencer]], ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', accessed 2 June 2011;  see also [http://www.preecefamilyhistory.co.uk/grobirs94_95.htm Preece Family History and One Name Study (1894\u20131895)], accessed 2 June 2011</ref><ref>Elliott, Vicky. [http://articles.sfgate.com/1998-07-19/news/17726967_1_paintings-patricia-preece-flesh/2 ''Lives Laid Bare \u2013 The second wife of the British painter Stanley Spencer...\"]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} SF Gate, ''San Francisco Chronicle'', 19 July 1998, accessed 2 June 2011</ref>  The three arrived at the lake at about 4 pm that day.  In 1923, Winifred Isabel Emery related to Gilbert's biographers her recollection of what happened on that day:\n\n<blockquote>Sir William Gilbert was teaching me to swim, and he invited me and a pupil of mine [Ruby Preece] to Grim's Dyke on May 29th. We met him at Harrow Station and motored to Grim's Dyke and went straight to the bathing pool. My pupil and I were in the water before Sir William had made an appearance. It was a very hot day, but the water struck very cold. My pupil was a much better swimmer than I, and soon outdistanced me. We were both unaware that the lake was very deep further out, and presently she shrieked out \"Oh, Miss Emery, I am drowning!\" I called Sir William, who was on the steps, and he called out to her not to be frightened, and that he was coming. He swam out to her very quickly, and I heard him say: \"Put your hands on my shoulder and don't struggle.\" This she did, but almost immediately she called out that he had sunk under her and had not come up. We both called to him, but got no answer. I tried to reach them, but got out of my depth and could do nothing but call for help. My pupil managed to struggle to the bank, and presently the gardener came and got out a boat, but it seemed a long time before they recovered the body.<ref name=Dark/></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Gilbert's lake.jpg|thumb|left|The lake, seen on 29 May 2011]]\nAt the [[coroner]]'s inquest, Preece stated, \"I found that I could not stand and called out and Sir William swam to me. I put my hand on his shoulder and I felt him suddenly sink. I thought he would come up again. My feet were on the mud then. Miss Emery called for help and the gardeners came with the boat.\"  Gilbert had \"died instantly of the heart attack\".<ref>Stedman, p. 346</ref>  Once his body was recovered, it was laid out in the billiard room (now the hotel's restaurant) at Grim's Dyke.<ref>Eden, D. J., ''W.S. Gilbert \u2013 Appearance and Reality'', Sir Arthur Sullivan Society (2003), p. 111</ref> The family doctor, W.W. Shackleton, and Daniel Wilson of Bushey Heath Cottage Hospital, later certified that Gilbert had died at about 4.20 pm that afternoon of [[Syncope (medicine)|syncope]] (heart failure) brought on by excessive exertion. The coroner's jury, also meeting in the billiard room at Grim's Dyke two days later, on 31 May 1911, recorded a verdict of accidental death.\n\nShortly thereafter, Lady Gilbert had the lake closed off and largely drained.<ref name=Goodman17>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), pp. 17\u201318</ref>   The incident is described in the documentary ''[[Metro-Land (1973 film)|Metro-Land]]''. Over the century since then, silt has built up in the mostly drained lake and trees and other vegetation have grown, dividing the lake into smaller ponds.  In 2011, the rare [[Great Crested Newt]] was found living near these ponds.<ref>Proctor, Ian. [http://www.harrowobserver.co.uk/west-london-news/local-harrow-news/2011/08/04/lake-where-w-s-gilbert-died-gets-a-revamp-116451-29180156/ \"Lake where W S Gilbert died gets a revamp\"]. ''Harrow Observer'', 4 August 2011</ref>\n\n==Film location==\n[[File:Grim's Dyke Hotel, from the garden. - geograph.org.uk - 311183.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The house seen from the garden]]\nThe dramatic architecture of this Victorian country house, and its typically English interior, have made it attractive as a film and television location.<ref>[http://www.grimsdyke.com/about-us/film-tv \"Film & TV\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830103651/http://www.grimsdyke.com/about-us/film-tv/ |date=2016-08-30 }}, GrimsDyke.com, accessed 6 August 2016</ref>  The following television shows and films, among others, used Grim's Dyke as a location:\n*''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'' (1961) TV series; episodes include ''Game''<ref>Smith, David K. [http://theavengers.tv/forever/king-1.htm \"Episode 141: Tara King Era, 'Game'\"], Theavengerstv.com, 17 June 2006, accessed 6 August 2016</ref>\n*''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'' (1962) TV series; two episodes\n*''[[It Happened Here]]'' (1966) \n*''[[Doctor Who]]'': ''[[The Evil of the Daleks]]'' (1967) TV series; episodes 3 and 4\n*''[[The Blood Beast Terror]]'' (1968)\n*''[[Curse of the Crimson Altar]]'' (1968)\n*''[[The Champions]]'' (1968) TV series\n*''[[The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie (film)|The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie]]'' (1969)\n*''[[Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased)]]'' (1969) TV series; episode ''[[You Can Always Find a Fall Guy]]''\n*''[[Department S (TV series)|Department S]]'' (1969) TV series; episodes include ''Handicap Dead'' (1969) and ''The Bones of Byrom Blain'' (1970)\n*''[[Futtock's End]]'' (1970)\n*''[[Cry of the Banshee]]'' (1970)\n*''[[The Adventurer (TV series)|The Adventurer]]'' (1972\u201373) TV series\n*''[[Spyder's Web]]'' (1972) TV series\n*''[[Endless Night (1972 film)|Endless Night]]'' (1972)\n*''[[Metro-Land (1973 film)|Metro-Land]]'' (1973 documentary by [[John Betjeman]])\n*''[[Sliding Doors]]'' (1998) film\n*''[[EastEnders]]'' (2003) TV series \n*''[[Little Britain]]'' (2004) TV series\n*''[[Holby City]]'' TV series\n*''[[One Chance (film)|One Chance]]'' (2013 film)\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:This house designed by NORMAN SHAW Architect for FREDERICK GOODALL Painter was later the home of W.S. GILBERT Writer and librettist.jpg|[[Blue plaque]] at Grim's Dyke\nFile:Grims-dyke-front.jpg|Another view of the main entrance\nFile:Grims-dyke-library-bar.jpg|The Library Bar, formerly Gilbert's library\nFile:Grims-dyke-music-room.jpg|The Music Room\nFile:Grims-dyke-view.jpg|Grim's Dyke from the garden\nFile:Grims-dyke-gatehouse.jpg|The Gatehouse\nFile:Grims-dyke-1891.jpg|Grim's Dyke viewed from the dyke in 1891\nFile:Grims-dyke-hall-1891.jpg|Gilbert's [[model ship|model]] of [[HMS Queen (1839)|HMS ''Queen'']] at Grim's Dyke\nFile:Grims-dyke-porch-1891.jpg|Gilbert in the porch\nFile:Gilbert-library-working-1891.jpg|Gilbert at work in the library\nFile:Grims-dyke-dining-room-1891.jpg|The dining room in 1891\nFile:Grims-dyke-drawing-room-1891.jpg|The drawing room in 1891\nFile:Soho Square Charles II.JPG| [[Caius Gabriel Cibber|Cibber's]] [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], now in London's [[Soho Square]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Ainger|first=Michael|year=2002|title=Gilbert and Sullivan\u2013A Dual Biography|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-514769-3}}\n*Dark, Sidney and Rowland Grey. ''W. S. Gilbert: His Life and Letters'', Methuen & Co Ltd, London (1923)\n*Goodman, Andrew (2009). ''Grim's Dyke: A Short History of the House and Its Owners'', Glittering Prizes {{ISBN|978 1 85811 550 4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Stedman|first=Jane W.|year=1996|title=W. S. Gilbert, A Classic Victorian & His Theatre|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-816174-3}}\n\n==External links==\nListed building entries at [[Images of England]] for:\n* {{NHLE |num=1079676 |desc=Grims Dyke House}} (Grade II*)\n* {{NHLE |num=1193943 |desc=The gatehouse of the above}} (Grade II)\n* {{NHLE |num=1236305 |desc=Statue}} (Grade II) of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]]\n\n*[http://www.grimsdyke.com Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110929005712/http://www.grimsdyke.com/pdf/2011-05-09-newsletter.pdf Photos of Grim's Dyke and gardens]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=mwkMAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA355 \"Grim's Dyke\"] in ''Architecture: A monthly magazine of architectural art'', pp.&nbsp;355\u201368, vol. 2 (1897) Tolbot House\n*[http://londonundone.org.uk/2014/08/24/grims-dyke/ Podcast about Grim's Dyke], with interviewer Catherine Cartwright, by ''London Undone'' (2014)\n\n{{coord|51.6232|-0.3522|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Houses in the London Borough of Harrow]]\n[[Category:Hotels in London]]\n[[Category:Gilbert and Sullivan]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed houses in London]]\n[[Category:Country houses in London]]\n[[Category:Richard Norman Shaw buildings]]\n[[Category:History of the London Borough of Harrow]]\n[[Category:History of Middlesex]]\n[[Category:Middlesex]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in the London Borough of Harrow]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in the London Borough of Harrow]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the prehistoric earthworks in southern England|Grim's Ditch|the Roman fortifications in central Scotland|Antonine Wall}}\n[[File:grims-dyke-main.jpg|thumb|300px|The main entrance|alt=]]\n'''Grim's Dyke''' (sometimes called '''Graeme's Dyke''' until late 1891)<ref name=How>How, Harry. [https://www.gsarchive.net/gilbert/interviews/strand_article.html Illustrated Interviews: No. IV \u2013 Mr. W. S. Gilbert\"], ''[[The Strand Magazine]]'', Vol. 2, October 1891, pp. 330\u201341, reprinted at ''The Gilbert and Sullivan Archive'', 20 November 2011</ref> is the name of a house and estate in [[Harrow Weald]], in northwest London, England. The house was built from 1870 to 1872 by [[Richard Norman Shaw]] for painter [[Frederick Goodall]] and named after the nearby prehistoric earthwork known as [[Grim's Ditch (Harrow)|Grim's Ditch]].\n\nThe house is best known as the home of the dramatist [[W. S. Gilbert]], of the opera partnership [[Gilbert and Sullivan]], who lived and farmed there for the last two decades of his life.  He died while attempting to save a girl from drowning in his lake. Lady Gilbert and the Gilberts' ward, [[Nancy McIntosh]], lived there until her death in 1936. The statue of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] now found in [[Soho Square]] stood on the property from about 1880 to 1938. The house was then used as a rehabilitation centre until 1963.\n\nFrom 1963, the house was used mainly as a location for films and television, including ''[[Futtocks End]]'' and ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]''. It was converted into Grim's Dyke Hotel in 1970 but continues to be used as a film location. The hotel retains 30 of the original 110 acres of land that Gilbert purchased with the house.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Grims-Dyke-The-Art-Journal-1881.jpg|thumb|left|Grim's Dyke from the dyke in 1881]]\nThe house was designed in 1870 by [[Richard Norman Shaw]] for the [[Victorian era]] painter [[Frederick Goodall]], who had purchased {{convert|110|acre|km2}} of land<ref>Ainger, p. 320</ref> at [[Harrow Weald]] in 1856, but he did not begin to build until a lease on the property expired.  Shaw's design for the house included aspects of [[Gothic revival]]ism, added to a late-Elizabethan style, which included high red-tiled gables, tall clustered chimneys and leaded lights. To the north of the house, Shaw built a small lodge, a walled garden and various outhouses and a stable block, later converted into garages by [[W. S. Gilbert]] for his collection of motorcars.<ref>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 6</ref> Over the dyke (now a duck pond) Shaw built two stone bridges, which incorporated [[flint]] from the ruined church at [[Stanmore]].<ref>Coincidentally, Gilbert's ashes were buried in the churchyard of this church after his death in 1911.</ref>  Construction on the house was completed in 1872.  Goodall's ground-floor studio was built on a north-south axis in order to catch the light. Goodall sold the property in 1880 to Robert Herriot of [[Hambros Bank]], who added a billiard room in 1883.<ref name=Goodman7>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 7</ref>  [[Windsor Castle]] is visible from the house.<ref name=How/>\n\n[[File:gilbert-library-1891.jpg|thumb|right|[[W.S. Gilbert|Gilbert]] in his library in 1891]]\nW. S. Gilbert purchased the property in August 1890 for \u00a34,000.<ref>Stedman, p. 278.</ref>  He made various additions and alterations to the property, including an elaborate fireplace of Cornish [[alabaster]] in Goodall's studio, which became Gilbert's drawing/music room.  At the house, Gilbert wrote his last ten works from an armchair in his library overlooking the croquet lawn.<ref>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 12</ref>  Gilbert also had an observatory for stargazing.<ref name=How/>\n\n[[Arthur Sullivan]] visited Grim's Dyke with his nephew, [[Herbert Sullivan|Herbert]], on 27 May 1893.<ref>Wolfson, John. ''Final Curtain: The Last Gilbert and Sullivan Operas'', Chappell in association with A. Deutsch, London (1976) p. 28 {{ISBN|0-903443-12-0}}</ref> They stayed at the house for three days while Sullivan worked with Gilbert to finalise ''[[Utopia, Limited]]''.<ref name=\"Goodman Grim's Dyke, p. 17\">Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 17</ref>  At the house, Gilbert had a vinery, [[apiary]], orchards and a farm, with [[Jersey cattle]], horses, pigs and fowl.<ref name=How/>  He also kept a variety of exotic animals including monkeys, lemurs, a lynx and many others.<ref name=Nancy>McIntosh, Nancy.  \"The Late Sir W. S. Gilbert's Pets\", ''Country Life'', 3 June 1911, reprinted in ''W. S. Gilbert Society Journal'', Brian Jones (ed.), Vol. 2, No. 18: Winter 2005, pp. 548\u201356; and McIntosh, Nancy.  \"Sir William Gilbert's Lemurs\", ''The Strand Magazine'', November 1909, vol. 38, pp. 604-09</ref>  Lady Gilbert designed the 30 acres of ornamental gardens at the house, which remain as the hotel grounds.<ref name=Gardens>Glenn, Jill. [http://www.optimamagazine.co.uk/read/leisure/places-to-go/596-lady-gilberts-gardens \"Lady Gilbert's Gardens\"], ''Optima Magazine'', 10 June 2011, accessed January 25, 2012</ref>  After Gilbert's death in 1911, Lady Gilbert and the Gilberts' companion, [[Nancy McIntosh]], continued to live there until Lady Gilbert's own death in 1936.<ref name=Nancy/><ref>Stone, David. [https://www.gsarchive.net/whowaswho/M/McIntoshNancy.htm Nancy McIntosh] at ''Who Was Who in the D'Oyly Carte Opera Company'', 17 August 2005, accessed 3 June 2011</ref>\n\n[[File:Gilbert-library.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Gilbert in the library in later years]]\nAfter Lady Gilbert's death, the contents of the house, apart from a few items kept by Nancy McIntosh, were sold at public auction on 17 and 18 March 1937, realising \u00a34,600. The house was acquired jointly by the [[Middlesex County Council]] and the [[London County Council]], who leased it to the North West Regional Hospital Board from 1937 to 1962, at first as a rehabilitation centre for women suffering from tuberculosis (the house was used by the services during the World War II).<ref name=HistoryPHP>Goodman, Andrew. [http://www.grimsdyke.com/about-us/history/ History], Grimsdyke.com, accessed 26 March 2014</ref>  Following the war, both sexes were admitted,<ref>Goodman, Andrew. ''Gilbert and Sullivan's London'', Hippocrene Books (1988) {{ISBN|0-87052-441-0}}</ref> and from 1948 only male patients were admitted. From 1963, the house was used primarily as a location for films and television, including ''[[Futtock's End]]'' with [[Ronnie Barker]].  It was converted into a hotel in 1970.<ref name=HistoryPHP/> It was featured in John Betjeman's acclaimed television documentary ''[[Metro-Land (1973 film)|Metro-Land]]'' (1973).  The hotel was seen in an [[EastEnders off set episodes#2003|off set episode of ''EastEnders'']] in 2003.\n\nThe house and its gatehouse are both [[listed building]]s.  [[Harrow Council]] owns the building and the remaining 30 acres of the estate and has leased them to the hotel since 1970.<ref name=Gardens/>  The hotel and estate were refurbished in 1996 at a cost of \u00a33 million.<ref name=HistoryPHP/> Presentations of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] operas and other entertainments are regularly held.  The remainder of the lands have been separated from the hotel and are being sold by Harrow Council as \"Grimsdyke Farm\".<ref>[http://www.fwi.co.uk/Articles/2010/01/20/119602/Gilbert-and-Sullivan-estate-up-for-grabs.htm \"Gilbert and Sullivan estate up for grabs\"], Reed Business Information Ltd, 20 January 2010</ref>\n\nThe name Grim's Dyke is sometimes used to refer to a nearby earthwork known as [[Grim's Ditch (Harrow)|Grim's Ditch]] which runs from Pinner Hill to [[RAF Bentley Priory|Bentley Priory]].\n\n==Statue of Charles II==\n[[File:grims-dyke-lake.jpg|thumb|right|260px|The statue of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] in the lake in 1891]]\nA statue of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] was carved by Danish sculptor [[Caius Gabriel Cibber]] in 1681 and placed at the centre of [[Soho Square]] in London.  By the early 19th century, the statue was described as being 'in a most wretched mutilated state; and the inscriptions on the base of the pedestal quite illegible'.<ref name=Cibber>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=41027&strquery=Cibber \"Soho Square Area: Portland Estate: Soho Square Garden\"] in ''Survey of London'' volumes 33 and 34 (1966) St Anne Soho, pp. 51-53. Date accessed: 12 January 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 1875, the statue was removed during alterations in the square by T. Blackwell, of [[Crosse and Blackwell]], the venerable canned and bottled foodstuffs firm, who gave it for safekeeping to his friend, Goodall, with the intention that it might be restored.<ref name=Cibber/>  Goodall placed the statue on an island in his lake at Grim's Dyke, where it remained while Gilbert owned the property.  In her will, Lady Gilbert directed that the statue be returned, and it was restored to Soho Square in 1938.<ref>Minogue, Tim. [http://www.spab.org.uk/cornerstone-magazine/articles-from-cornerstone/soho-farewell-then-/ Soho farewell then\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927120947/http://www.spab.org.uk/cornerstone-magazine/articles-from-cornerstone/soho-farewell-then-/ |date=2011-09-27 }}. SBAP.org, 2009, accessed 2 June 2011</ref>\n\n==Gilbert's lake and death==\nThe lake, which is some way from the house, beyond the ornamental gardens, was considerably extended by Gilbert during his time at Grim's Dyke. Work on digging out the lake began in 1899, with Gilbert himself assisting in the task. Eventually it covered about one and a half [[acre]]s, with an island in the middle, a [[Punt (boat)|punt]] house and changing hut, and an artificial waterfall that was ceremonially turned on in December 1899. The lake was drained and refilled each year, to keep the water clear, and was stocked with [[trout]].<ref>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), p. 14</ref>  In 1905 the lake was extended again to a roughly rectangular shape, measuring 170 [[yard]]s by 50 yards. When Gilbert lived at Grim's Dyke he swam in the lake every day from March to September.<ref name=\"Goodman Grim's Dyke, p. 17\"/>\n[[File:gilberts-lake-1899.jpg|thumb|right|Gilbert's Lake in 1899]]\nOn 29 May 1911 Gilbert had arranged to give a swimming lesson in the lake to two local girls,<ref>Crowther, Andrew. [http://diamond.boisestate.edu/gas/html/gilbert_l.html ''The Life of W. S. Gilbert''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513163810/http://diamond.boisestate.edu/gas/html/gilbert_l.html |date=2008-05-13 }}, The Gilbert and Sullivan Archive, accessed 1 June 2011</ref> Winifred Isabel Emery (1890\u20131972), a teacher<ref>[http://www.1911census.co.uk/search/results5.aspx?x=2080537253 \"76 Weldon Crescent, Harrow County\"]. UK 1911 Census, accessed 6 June 2011 {{subscription}}</ref> and niece of the actors [[Cyril Maude]] and [[Winifred Emery]],<ref>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/76473?docPos=1 Biography] of [[David Gascoyne]], ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', accessed 2 June 2011</ref><ref name=Dark>Dark and Grey, pp. 222\u2013223</ref> and her 17-year-old pupil [[Ruby Vivian Preece]].<ref name=\"Goodman Grim's Dyke, p. 17\"/><ref>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/36211?docPos=3 Biography] of [[Stanley Spencer]], ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', accessed 2 June 2011;  see also [http://www.preecefamilyhistory.co.uk/grobirs94_95.htm Preece Family History and One Name Study (1894\u20131895)], accessed 2 June 2011</ref><ref>Elliott, Vicky. [http://articles.sfgate.com/1998-07-19/news/17726967_1_paintings-patricia-preece-flesh/2 ''Lives Laid Bare \u2013 The second wife of the British painter Stanley Spencer...\"]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} SF Gate, ''San Francisco Chronicle'', 19 July 1998, accessed 2 June 2011</ref>  The three arrived at the lake at about 4 pm that day.  In 1923, Winifred Isabel Emery related to Gilbert's biographers her recollection of what happened on that day:\n\n<blockquote>Sir William Gilbert was teaching me to swim, and he invited me and a pupil of mine [Ruby Preece] to Grim's Dyke on May 29th. We met him at Harrow Station and motored to Grim's Dyke and went straight to the bathing pool. My pupil and I were in the water before Sir William had made an appearance. It was a very hot day, but the water struck very cold. My pupil was a much better swimmer than I, and soon outdistanced me. We were both unaware that the lake was very deep further out, and presently she shrieked out \"Oh, Miss Emery, I am drowning!\" I called Sir William, who was on the steps, and he called out to her not to be frightened, and that he was coming. He swam out to her very quickly, and I heard him say: \"Put your hands on my shoulder and don't struggle.\" This she did, but almost immediately she called out that he had sunk under her and had not come up. We both called to him, but got no answer. I tried to reach them, but got out of my depth and could do nothing but call for help. My pupil managed to struggle to the bank, and presently the gardener came and got out a boat, but it seemed a long time before they recovered the body.<ref name=Dark/></blockquote>\n\n[[File:Gilbert's lake.jpg|thumb|left|The lake, seen on 29 May 2011]]\nAt the [[coroner]]'s inquest, Preece stated, \"I found that I could not stand and called out and Sir William swam to me. I put my hand on his shoulder and I felt him suddenly sink. I thought he would come up again. My feet were on the mud then. Miss Emery called for help and the gardeners came with the boat.\"  Gilbert had \"died instantly of the heart attack\".<ref>Stedman, p. 346</ref>  Once his body was recovered, it was laid out in the billiard room (now the hotel's restaurant) at Grim's Dyke.<ref>Eden, D. J., ''W.S. Gilbert \u2013 Appearance and Reality'', Sir Arthur Sullivan Society (2003), p. 111</ref> The family doctor, W.W. Shackleton, and Daniel Wilson of Bushey Heath Cottage Hospital, later certified that Gilbert had died at about 4.20 pm that afternoon of [[Syncope (medicine)|syncope]] (heart failure) brought on by excessive exertion. The coroner's jury, also meeting in the billiard room at Grim's Dyke two days later, on 31 May 1911, recorded a verdict of accidental death.\n\nShortly thereafter, Lady Gilbert had the lake closed off and largely drained.<ref name=Goodman17>Goodman (''Grim's Dyke''), pp. 17\u201318</ref>   The incident is described in the documentary ''[[Metro-Land (1973 film)|Metro-Land]]''. Over the century since then, silt has built up in the mostly drained lake and trees and other vegetation have grown, dividing the lake into smaller ponds.  In 2011, the rare [[Great Crested Newt]] was found living near these ponds.<ref>Proctor, Ian. [http://www.harrowobserver.co.uk/west-london-news/local-harrow-news/2011/08/04/lake-where-w-s-gilbert-died-gets-a-revamp-116451-29180156/ \"Lake where W S Gilbert died gets a revamp\"]. ''Harrow Observer'', 4 August 2011</ref>\n\n==Film location==\n[[File:Grim's Dyke Hotel, from the garden. - geograph.org.uk - 311183.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The house seen from the garden]]\nThe dramatic architecture of this Victorian country house, and its typically English interior, have made it attractive as a film and television location.<ref>[http://www.grimsdyke.com/about-us/film-tv \"Film & TV\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830103651/http://www.grimsdyke.com/about-us/film-tv/ |date=2016-08-30 }}, GrimsDyke.com, accessed 6 August 2016</ref>  The following television shows and films, among others, used Grim's Dyke as a location:\n*''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'' (1961) TV series (episodes include \"Game\")<ref>Smith, David K. [http://theavengers.tv/forever/king-1.htm \"Episode 141: Tara King Era, 'Game'\"], Theavengerstv.com, 17 June 2006, accessed 6 August 2016</ref>\n*''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'' (1962) TV series (two episodes)\n*''[[It Happened Here]]'' (1966) \n*''[[Doctor Who]]'': \"[[The Evil of the Daleks]]\": (1967) TV series (episodes 3 and 4)\n*''[[The Blood Beast Terror]]'' (1968)\n*''[[Curse of the Crimson Altar]]'' (1968)\n*''[[The Champions]]'' (1968) TV series\n*''[[The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie (film)|The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie]]'' (1969)\n*''[[Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased)]]'' (1969) TV series; episode ''[[You Can Always Find a Fall Guy]]''\n*''[[Department S (TV series)|Department S]]'' (1969) TV series; episodes include ''Handicap Dead'' (1969) and ''The Bones of Byrom Blain'' (1970)\n*''[[Futtock's End]]'' (1970)\n*''[[Cry of the Banshee]]'' (1970)\n*''[[The Adventurer (TV series)|The Adventurer]]'' (1972\u201373) TV series\n*''[[Spyder's Web]]'' (1972) TV series\n*''[[Endless Night (1972 film)|Endless Night]]'' (1972)\n*''[[Metro-Land (1973 film)|Metro-Land]]'' (1973 documentary by [[John Betjeman]])\n*''[[Sliding Doors]]'' (1998) film\n*''[[EastEnders]]'' (2003) TV series \n*''[[Little Britain]]'' (2004) TV series\n*''[[Holby City]]'' TV series\n*''[[One Chance (film)|One Chance]]'' (2013 film)\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:This house designed by NORMAN SHAW Architect for FREDERICK GOODALL Painter was later the home of W.S. GILBERT Writer and librettist.jpg|[[Blue plaque]] at Grim's Dyke\nFile:Grims-dyke-front.jpg|Another view of the main entrance\nFile:Grims-dyke-library-bar.jpg|The Library Bar, formerly Gilbert's library\nFile:Grims-dyke-music-room.jpg|The Music Room\nFile:Grims-dyke-view.jpg|Grim's Dyke from the garden\nFile:Grims-dyke-gatehouse.jpg|The Gatehouse\nFile:Grims-dyke-1891.jpg|Grim's Dyke viewed from the dyke in 1891\nFile:Grims-dyke-hall-1891.jpg|Gilbert's [[model ship|model]] of [[HMS Queen (1839)|HMS ''Queen'']] at Grim's Dyke\nFile:Grims-dyke-porch-1891.jpg|Gilbert in the porch\nFile:Gilbert-library-working-1891.jpg|Gilbert at work in the library\nFile:Grims-dyke-dining-room-1891.jpg|The dining room in 1891\nFile:Grims-dyke-drawing-room-1891.jpg|The drawing room in 1891\nFile:Soho Square Charles II.JPG| [[Caius Gabriel Cibber|Cibber's]] [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], now in London's [[Soho Square]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Ainger|first=Michael|year=2002|title=Gilbert and Sullivan\u2013A Dual Biography|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-514769-3}}\n*Dark, Sidney and Rowland Grey. ''W. S. Gilbert: His Life and Letters'', Methuen & Co Ltd, London (1923)\n*Goodman, Andrew (2009). ''Grim's Dyke: A Short History of the House and Its Owners'', Glittering Prizes {{ISBN|978 1 85811 550 4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Stedman|first=Jane W.|year=1996|title=W. S. Gilbert, A Classic Victorian & His Theatre|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-816174-3}}\n\n==External links==\nListed building entries at [[Images of England]] for:\n* {{NHLE |num=1079676 |desc=Grims Dyke House}} (Grade II*)\n* {{NHLE |num=1193943 |desc=The gatehouse of the above}} (Grade II)\n* {{NHLE |num=1236305 |desc=Statue}} (Grade II) of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]]\n\n*[http://www.grimsdyke.com Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110929005712/http://www.grimsdyke.com/pdf/2011-05-09-newsletter.pdf Photos of Grim's Dyke and gardens]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=mwkMAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA355 \"Grim's Dyke\"] in ''Architecture: A monthly magazine of architectural art'', pp.&nbsp;355\u201368, vol. 2 (1897) Tolbot House\n*[http://londonundone.org.uk/2014/08/24/grims-dyke/ Podcast about Grim's Dyke], with interviewer Catherine Cartwright, by ''London Undone'' (2014)\n\n{{coord|51.6232|-0.3522|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Houses in the London Borough of Harrow]]\n[[Category:Hotels in London]]\n[[Category:Gilbert and Sullivan]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed houses in London]]\n[[Category:Country houses in London]]\n[[Category:Richard Norman Shaw buildings]]\n[[Category:History of the London Borough of Harrow]]\n[[Category:History of Middlesex]]\n[[Category:Middlesex]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in the London Borough of Harrow]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in the London Borough of Harrow]]\n", "name_user": "Clamias", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilm location", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grim%27s_Dyke"}
{"title_page": "Hanae Mori", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2011}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2011}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hanae Mori\n| image              = Hanae Mori 1974.jpg\n| alt                = Hanae Mori in 1974\n| caption            = Hanae Mori in 1974.\n| native_name        = \u68ee \u82f1\u6075\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| pronunciation      = Mori Hanae\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1926|01|08}}\n| birth_place        = [[Muikaichi, Shimane]]\n| nationality        = Japanese\n| alma_mater         = [[Tokyo Women's Christian University]]\n| occupation         = [[Fashion design]]er\n| years_active       = 1951\u20132004\n| known_for          = Fashion design\n| spouse             = Kenzo Mori<ref name=\"People1976\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/who-says-butterflies-are-free-on-a-hanae-mori-gown-they-cost-700-and-up-vol-6-no-25/|title=Who Says Butterflies Are Free? on a Hanae Mori Gown, They Cost $700 and Up|last=|first=|date=20 December 1976|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n| children           = 2\n| honours            = [[Medals of Honor (Japan)|Medal of Honor (Japan), purple ribbon]] (1988)\n[[Legion of Honour|Legion of Honour (France)]] (1989)\n[[Order of Culture|Order of Culture (Japan)]] (1996)\n| website            = https://hanaemoriparfums.com/\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Hanae Mori'''|\u68ee \u82f1\u6075|Mori Hanae|{{IPAc-en|h|\u0259|\u02cc|n|\u0251\u02d0|e\u026a|_|\u02c8|m|\u0254\u02d0|r|i}}, born January 8, 1926}} is a [[fashion design]]er in [[Japan]]. She is one of only two Japanese women to have presented her collections on the runways of Paris and New York, and the first Asian woman to be admitted as an official ''[[haute couture]]'' design house by the [[f\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise de la couture]]<ref name=\"The Japan Times - 18 April 2015 - Hanae Mori Haute Couture: Hanae Mori \u2014 The Work and Style\">{{cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/events/2015/04/14/art-guide/hanae-mori-haute-couture/#.VZKbZ1Jq2CU|title=Hanae Mori Haute Couture: Hanae Mori \u2014 The Work and Style|date=18 April 2015|work=[[The Japan Times]]|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> in France. Her fashion house, opened in Japan in 1951, grew to become a $500 million international business by the 1990s.\n\n==Career==\nMori was born in [[Muikaichi, Shimane]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://jfw.jp/en/topics/interview/hanae-mori/|title=Hanae Mori|website=Tokyo Fashion Week|language=en|access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> After graduating from [[Tokyo Women's Christian University]], she married and attended dress-making school.<ref name=\":1\" /> She opened her first atelier in 1951 and over the next several years designed costumes for hundreds of movies.  In 1965, she presented her first New York collection, \"East Meets West.\" Twelve years later, she opened an haute couture showroom in [[Paris]], leading to her appointment as a member of [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise de la couture|La Chambre Syndicale de la Couture Parisienne]].\n\nMori designed three consecutive uniforms for the [[flight attendant]]s of [[Japan Air Lines]] (JAL). The first uniform was worn from 1967 to 1970;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jal.com/en/history/uniform/uniform_04.html|title=History of JAL Uniforms - Fourth Generation Uniform (1967-1970)|website=Japan Airlines|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> the second, which created a sensation by featuring a [[miniskirt]], worn from 1970 to 1977;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jal.com/en/history/uniform/uniform_05.html|title=History of JAL Uniforms - Fifth Generation Uniform (1970-1977)|website=Japan Airlines|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> and the third worn from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jal.com/en/history/uniform/uniform_06.html|title=History of JAL Uniforms - Sixth Generation Uniform (1977-1988)|website=Japan Airlines|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> From 1989 to 1996, Mori employed [[Dominique Sirop]] as a designer. He became a ''[[List of grand couturiers|grand couturier]]'' in 1997. In 1992, Mori designed the official uniform for the Japanese Delegation to the [[1992 Summer Olympics|Barcelona Olympics]] and, in 1994, the official uniform for the Japanese Delegation to the [[1994 Winter Olympics|Lillehammer Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrimptoncouture.com/blogs/curated/94919809-designer-spotlight-hanae-mori|title=Designer Spotlight: Hanae Mori|last=Federau|first=Cherie|date=31 March 2016|website=Shrimpton Couture|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> Also in 1993, [[Masako, Crown Princess of Japan]] wore a sleeveless white gown designed by Mori for her wedding ceremony.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/the-princess-bride-vol-39-no-24/|title=The Princess Bride|last=Sanz|first=Cynthia|date=21 June 1993|website=People|language=en|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> Mori had the patronage of [[Masako, Crown Princess of Japan]], [[Hillary Clinton]], [[Nancy Reagan]] and Princess Grace of Monaco [[Grace Kelly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vintagecouture.com/collections/hanae-mori|title=Hanae Mori \u2013 Vintage Couture|website=www.vintagecouture.com|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n\nAmidst company financial struggles, Mori sold the ready-to-wear and licensed apparel operations in January 2002 to an investment group formed by Japanese trading company [[Mitsui & Co.]] and the Rothschild group in Britain.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fashionmodeldirectory.com/designers/hanae-mori/|title=Hanae Mori|website=FMD|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2001/12/29/business/hanae-mori-to-sell-part-of-operations/|title=Hanae Mori to sell part of operations|last=|first=|date=29 December 2001|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=15 October 2019|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref> Opting for fast-track corporate rehabilitation, the company then applied to the [[Tokyo District Court]] for protection from its creditors on May 30, 2002, as it had {{Currency|10.1 billion|JPY}} ({{Currency|81 million|}}) in liabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Hanae+Mori+holds+1st+fashion+show+since+bankruptcy.-a091757984|title=Hanae Mori holds 1st fashion show since bankruptcy|website=www.thefreelibrary.com|publisher=Kyodo News International|orig-year=2002|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.just-style.com/news/fashion-house-hanae-mori-goes-bust_id86239.aspx|title=JAPAN: Fashion House Hanae Mori Goes Bust|date=31 May 2002|website=www.just-style.com|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nMori announced her retirement in June 2004, stating that she would be closing her fashion house after the Haute Couture Show for Fall 2004 in Paris.<ref name=\":0\" /> She held her last fashion show in July of that year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2004/07/09/national/hanae-mori-shows-her-final-collection-in-paris/|title=Hanae Mori shows her final collection in Paris|last=|first=|date=9 July 2004|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=14 October 2019|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n\n===Later life===\nMori has retired from the runway but still has a few boutiques in [[Tokyo]]'s [[Harajuku]] neighborhood, including one in the [[Hotel Okura]]. Her [[fragrance]] division, Hanae Mori Parfums, is still active and produces a series of acclaimed fragrances including Hanae Mori Butterfly for women, HM for Men and Hanae Mori Magical Moon for women. Hanae Mori Parfums are made in France and distributed worldwide. It can be purchased throughout the United States at stores such as [[Nordstrom]], [[Neiman Marcus]], [[Saks Fifth Avenue]], [[Bloomingdale's]], [[Macy's]] and [[Sephora]]. Hanae Moir Manuscrit is a line currently designed by Yu Amatsu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hanaemori-manuscrit.com/|title=Hanae Mori manuscrit|website=Hanae Mori manuscrit|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1988, she received a [[Medals of Honor (Japan)]] of Purple Ribbon by the [[Government of Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://middle-edge.jp/articles/I0001006|title=\u30c7\u30b6\u30a4\u30ca\u30fc\u68ee\u82f1\u6075\u3055\u3093\u306e\u30d5\u30a1\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u3068\u6587\u5316|last=10 November 2015|website=Middle Edge\uff08\u30df\u30c9\u30eb\u30a8\u30c3\u30b8\uff09|language=ja|trans-title=Designer Hanae Mori's fashion and culture|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> In 1989 Mori was awarded the [[French Legion of Honor]] by President [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]] of France. In 1996 Mori was awarded the [[Order of Culture]] by the [[Emperor of Japan]].\n\n==Style==\nMori signature design inspiration is the [[butterfly]]. In addition to serving clients including [[Princess Grace of Monaco]] and [[Crown Princess Masako]] of Japan, for whom Mori made a wedding gown, Mori has made costumes for operas including \"[[Madame Butterfly]]\" and \"[[Elektra (opera)|Elektra]]\", ballets including \"Cinderella\" and musicals such as the Japanese production of \"[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]\". She has created designs for [[shoes]], [[stockings]], [[gloves]], [[necktie|ties]], [[Belt (clothing)|belts]], [[handbag]]s, [[umbrella]]s, [[sunglasses]], [[aprons]], [[carpet]]s, and [[lacquerware]]. She also has a range of fragrances, including Hanae Mori and Hanae Mori Butterfly. Her published books include ''Hanae Mori 1960-1989 and Fashion \u2013 A Butterfly That Flew Across the Border''.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080907171526/http://www.fashionwindows.com/fashion_review/hanae_mori/default.asp ''Hanae Mori: A Life Of Fashion'' by Mari Davis, August 25, 2008, Fashion Windows] [not found]\n* [http://www.infomat.com/whoswho/hanaemori.html hanae mori, Fashion Designer, January 18, 2007, Fashion Infomat] [not found]\n\n==External links==\n* {{FMD designer}}\n* http://hanaemori-manuscrit.com/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mori, Hanae}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese fashion designers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Culture]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Honour]]\n[[Category:Tokyo Woman's Christian University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{No footnotes|date=April 2011}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2011}}{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hanae Mori\n| image              = Hanae Mori 1974.jpg\n| alt                = Hanae Mori in 1974\n| caption            = Hanae Mori in 1974.\n| native_name        = \u68ee \u82f1\u6075\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| pronunciation      = Mori Hanae\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1926|01|08}}\n| birth_place        = [[Muikaichi, Shimane]]\n| nationality        = Japanese\n| alma_mater         = [[Tokyo Women's Christian University]]\n| occupation         = [[Fashion design|Fashion designer]]\n| years_active       = 1951\u20132004\n| known_for          = Fashion design\n| spouse             = Kenzo Mori<ref name=\"People1976\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/who-says-butterflies-are-free-on-a-hanae-mori-gown-they-cost-700-and-up-vol-6-no-25/|title=Who Says Butterflies Are Free? on a Hanae Mori Gown, They Cost $700 and Up|last=|first=|date=20 December 1976|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 October 2019}}</ref>\n| children           = 2\n| honours            = [[Medals of Honor (Japan)|Medal of Honor (Japan), purple ribbon]] (1988)\n[[Legion of Honour|Legion of Honour (France)]] (1989)\n[[Order of Culture|Order of Culture (Japan)]] (1996)\n| website            = https://hanaemoriparfums.com/\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Hanae Mori'''|\u68ee \u82f1\u6075|Mori Hanae|{{IPAc-en|h|\u0259|\u02cc|n|\u0251\u02d0|e\u026a|_|\u02c8|m|\u0254\u02d0|r|i}}, born January 8, 1926}} is a [[Fashion design|fashion designer]] in [[Japan]]. She is one of only two Japanese women to have presented her collections on the runways of Paris and New York, and the first Asian woman to be admitted as an official ''[[haute couture]]'' design house by the [[f\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise de la couture]]<ref name=\"The Japan Times - 18 April 2015 - Hanae Mori Haute Couture: Hanae Mori \u2014 The Work and Style\">{{cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/events/2015/04/14/art-guide/hanae-mori-haute-couture/#.VZKbZ1Jq2CU|title=Hanae Mori Haute Couture: Hanae Mori \u2014 The Work and Style|date=18 April 2015|work=[[The Japan Times]]|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref> in France. Her fashion house, opened in Japan in 1951, grew to become a $500 million international business by the 1990s.\n\n==Career==\nMori was born in [[Muikaichi, Shimane]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://jfw.jp/en/topics/interview/hanae-mori/|title=Hanae Mori|website=Tokyo Fashion Week|language=en|access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> After graduating from [[Tokyo Women's Christian University]], she married and attended dress-making school.<ref name=\":1\" /> She opened her first atelier in 1951 and over the next several years designed costumes for hundreds of movies.  In 1965, she presented her first New York collection, \"East Meets West.\" Twelve years later, she opened an haute couture showroom in [[Paris]], leading to her appointment as a member of [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise de la couture|La Chambre Syndicale de la Couture Parisienne]].\n\nMori designed three consecutive uniforms for the [[Flight attendant|flight attendants]] of [[Japan Air Lines]] (JAL). The first uniform was worn from 1967 to 1970;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jal.com/en/history/uniform/uniform_04.html|title=History of JAL Uniforms - Fourth Generation Uniform (1967-1970)|website=Japan Airlines|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> the second, which created a sensation by featuring a [[miniskirt]], worn from 1970 to 1977;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jal.com/en/history/uniform/uniform_05.html|title=History of JAL Uniforms - Fifth Generation Uniform (1970-1977)|website=Japan Airlines|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> and the third worn from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jal.com/en/history/uniform/uniform_06.html|title=History of JAL Uniforms - Sixth Generation Uniform (1977-1988)|website=Japan Airlines|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> From 1989 to 1996, Mori employed [[Dominique Sirop]] as a designer. He became a ''[[List of grand couturiers|grand couturier]]'' in 1997. In 1992, Mori designed the official uniform for the Japanese Delegation to the [[1992 Summer Olympics|Barcelona Olympics]] and, in 1994, the official uniform for the Japanese Delegation to the [[1994 Winter Olympics|Lillehammer Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrimptoncouture.com/blogs/curated/94919809-designer-spotlight-hanae-mori|title=Designer Spotlight: Hanae Mori|last=Federau|first=Cherie|date=31 March 2016|website=Shrimpton Couture|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> Also in 1993, [[Masako, Crown Princess of Japan]] wore a sleeveless white gown designed by Mori for her wedding ceremony.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/the-princess-bride-vol-39-no-24/|title=The Princess Bride|last=Sanz|first=Cynthia|date=21 June 1993|website=People|language=en|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> Mori had the patronage of [[Masako, Crown Princess of Japan]], [[Hillary Clinton]], [[Nancy Reagan]] and Princess Grace of Monaco [[Grace Kelly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vintagecouture.com/collections/hanae-mori|title=Hanae Mori \u2013 Vintage Couture|website=www.vintagecouture.com|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n\nAmidst company financial struggles, Mori sold the ready-to-wear and licensed apparel operations in January 2002 to a investment group formed by Japanese trading company [[Mitsui & Co.]] and the Rothschild group in Britain.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fashionmodeldirectory.com/designers/hanae-mori/|title=Hanae Mori|website=FMD|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2001/12/29/business/hanae-mori-to-sell-part-of-operations/|title=Hanae Mori to sell part of operations|last=|first=|date=29 December 2001|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=15 October 2019|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref> Opting for fast-track corporate rehabilitation, the company then applied to the [[Tokyo District Court]] for protection from its creditors on May 30, 2002, as it had {{Currency|10.1 billion|JPY}} ({{Currency|81 million|}}) in liabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Hanae+Mori+holds+1st+fashion+show+since+bankruptcy.-a091757984|title=Hanae Mori holds 1st fashion show since bankruptcy|website=www.thefreelibrary.com|publisher=Kyodo News International|orig-year=2002|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.just-style.com/news/fashion-house-hanae-mori-goes-bust_id86239.aspx|title=JAPAN: Fashion House Hanae Mori Goes Bust|date=31 May 2002|website=www.just-style.com|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> \n\nMori announced her retirement in June 2004, stating that she would be closing her fashion house after the Haute Couture Show for Fall 2004 in Paris.<ref name=\":0\" /> She held her last fashion show in July of that year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2004/07/09/national/hanae-mori-shows-her-final-collection-in-paris/|title=Hanae Mori shows her final collection in Paris|last=|first=|date=9 July 2004|work=The Japan Times Online|access-date=14 October 2019|language=en-US|issn=0447-5763}}</ref>\n\n===Later life===\nMori has retired from the runway but still has a few boutiques in [[Tokyo]]'s [[Harajuku]] neighborhood, including one in the [[Hotel Okura]]. Her [[fragrance]] division, Hanae Mori Parfums, is still active and produces a series of acclaimed fragrances including Hanae Mori Butterfly for women, HM for Men and Hanae Mori Magical Moon for women. Hanae Mori Parfums are made in France and distributed worldwide. It can be purchased throughout the United States at stores such as [[Nordstrom]], [[Neiman Marcus]], [[Saks Fifth Avenue]], [[Bloomingdale's]], [[Macy's]] and [[Sephora]]. Hanae Moir Manuscrit is a line currently designed by Yu Amatsu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hanaemori-manuscrit.com/|title=Hanae Mori manuscrit|website=Hanae Mori manuscrit|accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1988, she received a [[Medals of Honor (Japan) ]] of Purple Ribbon by the [[Government of Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://middle-edge.jp/articles/I0001006|title=\u30c7\u30b6\u30a4\u30ca\u30fc\u68ee\u82f1\u6075\u3055\u3093\u306e\u30d5\u30a1\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u3068\u6587\u5316|last=10 November 2015|website=Middle Edge\uff08\u30df\u30c9\u30eb\u30a8\u30c3\u30b8\uff09|language=ja|trans-title=Designer Hanae Mori's fashion and culture|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> In 1989 Mori was awarded the [[French Legion of Honor]] by President [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]] of France. In 1996 Mori was awarded the [[Order of Culture]] by the [[Emperor of Japan]].\n\n==Style==\nMori signature design inspiration is the [[butterfly]]. In addition to serving clients including [[Princess Grace of Monaco]] and [[Crown Princess Masako]] of Japan, for whom Mori made a wedding gown, Mori has made costumes for operas including \"[[Madame Butterfly]]\" and \"[[Elektra (opera)|Elektra]]\", ballets including \"Cinderella\" and musicals such as the Japanese production of \"[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]\". She has created designs for [[shoes]], [[stockings]], [[gloves]], [[necktie|ties]], [[Belt (clothing)|belts]], [[handbag]]s, [[umbrella]]s, [[sunglasses]], [[aprons]], [[carpet]]s, and [[lacquerware]]. She also has a range of fragrances, including Hanae Mori and Hanae Mori Butterfly. Her published books include ''Hanae Mori 1960-1989 and Fashion \u2013 A Butterfly That Flew Across the Border''.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080907171526/http://www.fashionwindows.com/fashion_review/hanae_mori/default.asp ''Hanae Mori: A Life Of Fashion'' by Mari Davis, August 25, 2008, Fashion Windows] [not found]\n* [http://www.infomat.com/whoswho/hanaemori.html hanae mori, Fashion Designer, January 18, 2007, Fashion Infomat] [not found]\n\n==External links==\n* {{FMD designer}}\n* http://hanaemori-manuscrit.com/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mori, Hanae}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese fashion designers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Culture]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Honour]]\n[[Category:Tokyo Woman's Christian University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: a investment \u2192 an investment", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hanae_Mori"}
